{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657881"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:38:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:38:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20682"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20682"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13558"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94541"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13558"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20682"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77581"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"302"},{"type":"tags","id":"11585"},{"type":"tags","id":"11784"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32442"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32443"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94541"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with fever, confusion, and hypotension. Blood cultures are positive for gram-negative bacteria. Laboratory tests show elevated white blood cell count, thrombocytopenia, prolonged prothrombin time, elevated D-dimer levels, and blood glucose of 12.8 mmol/L (3.9-7.8) despite no history of diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary pathophysiological mechanism underlying this patient\u0027s condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Autoimmune destruction of platelets","Primary failure of adrenal hormone production","Excessive production of TNF and IL-1","Direct bacterial invasion of vascular endothelium","Bacterial endotoxin-induced myocardial depression"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is presenting with septic shock, characterized by hypotension, evidence of disseminated intravascular coagulation (thrombocytopenia, prolonged prothrombin time, elevated D-dimer), and metabolic disturbances (hyperglycemia). The primary pathophysiological mechanism is \u003Cstrong\u003Eexcessive production of TNF and IL-1\u003C/strong\u003E. In severe bacterial infections, large amounts of bacteria and their products in the bloodstream stimulate the production of enormous quantities of cytokines, particularly tumour necrosis factor (TNF) and interleukin-1 (IL-1). These cytokines mediate the clinical manifestations of septic shock.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoimmune destruction of platelets\u003C/strong\u003E - The thrombocytopenia in septic shock is due to consumption of platelets in disseminated intravascular coagulation, not autoimmune destruction.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary failure of adrenal hormone production\u003C/strong\u003E - Although adrenal insufficiency can occur in severe sepsis (relative adrenal insufficiency), it is not the primary mechanism of septic shock.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect bacterial invasion of vascular endothelium\u003C/strong\u003E - While bacteria can damage endothelium, the systemic effects of septic shock are primarily mediated by the host inflammatory response rather than direct bacterial invasion.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial endotoxin-induced myocardial depression\u003C/strong\u003E - While myocardial depression can occur in septic shock, it is a consequence of the inflammatory cascade rather than the primary mechanism. The depression is mediated by the same cytokines (TNF, IL-1) rather than being a direct effect of endotoxin.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESeptic shock represents one form of systemic inflammatory response syndrome (SIRS). The excessive cytokine production leads to vasodilation, increased vascular permeability, activation of the coagulation cascade, and metabolic derangements including insulin resistance and hyperglycemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Septic shock is characterized by hypotension, disseminated intravascular coagulation, and metabolic disturbances including insulin resistance and hyperglycemia.","Tumour necrosis factor (TNF) and interleukin-1 (IL-1) are key cytokines that mediate the pathophysiology of septic shock.","Septic shock is a form of systemic inflammatory response syndrome caused by severe bacterial infections."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 3, Inflammation and Repair; p. 102"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77581"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20682"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77581"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-24T12:53:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-24T12:54:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13558"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94541"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"headin